Aim: 
Search for a target value in an array using linear search.

Algorithm (brief):
Traverse array from index 0 to n-1.
If element equals target, return index.
If end reached, not found.

Code:
#include <stdio.h>

int linearSearch(int arr[], int n, int key) {
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        if (arr[i] == key) return i;
    return -1;
}

int main() {
    int arr[] = {5, 3, 8, 6, 2, 7};
    int n = sizeof(arr)/sizeof(arr[0]);
    int key = 6;
    int idx = linearSearch(arr, n, key);
    if (idx != -1) printf("Element %d found at index %d\n", key, idx);
    else printf("Element %d not found\n", key);
    return 0;
}


Sample Output:
Element 6 found at index 3


Result:
O(n) time; correct for unsorted arrays.
